Problem 01: The Nth root of an integer
Intuition:
The value of the nth root lies between 1 and m.
•If midⁿ == m, then mid is the answer.
•If midⁿ < m, the root must be larger, so search the right half.
•If midⁿ > m, the root must be smaller, so search the left half.

Since the search space is sorted, binary search reduces the number of checks significantly

Approach:
1.Set:
•low = 1
•high = m
2.While low <= high:
•Find mid = low + (high - low)/2
•Compute midⁿ
•If midⁿ == m, return mid
•If midⁿ < m, set low = mid + 1
•Otherwise, set high = mid - 1
3.If no integer root exists, return -1.

Time Complexity:
Binary search performs O(log m) iterations.
In each iteration, computing midⁿ takes O(n) multiplications.

Overall Time Complexity: O(nlogm)

Space Complexity:
Only a few variables are used.
O(1)
	​
Code:
class Solution {
  public:
      int check(long long mid, int n, int m) {
        long long ans = 1;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (ans > m / mid) return 2; 
            ans *= mid;
        }

        if (ans == m) return 1; 
        return 0;               
    }

public:
    int nthRoot(int n, int m) {
        if(m==0){
            return 0;
        }
        long long low = 1, high = m;

        while (low <= high) {
            long long mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

            int val = check(mid, n, m);

            if (val == 1)
                return mid;
            else if (val == 0)
                low = mid + 1;
            else
                high = mid - 1;
        }

        return -1;
    }
};
